result.execSummary:
The defendant Keshia Lynne Morris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Possession of a Controlled Substance-THC. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.
  • Possession of Drug Paraphernalia. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.

If enrolled in school, must carry at least 12 credits.
The defendant may not consume or possess alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns.
Eligible for expunction under 973.015 as long as all conditions have been complied with.

The defendant must submit a DNA sample.

The defendant must take all medications as prescribed by a treating physician and in the manner in which they are prescribed.

The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

The defendant must attend at least one AA/NA or similar meeting per week.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Keshia Lynne Morris in court with attorney Rick Terrence Cveykus.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 8:43 AM. Called 16CF23, 16CF37 and 16CF111. State - resolved - 16CF23 - dismiss entirely without prejudice, 16CF37 - #2  - amend to county ordinance of possession of THC with $1000.00 fine plus costs, #3 - amend to county ordinance of drug paraphanlia - $500 fine plus costs #1 - plead as alleged - withhold sentence and place on probation for 2 years with conditions of: court costs and same conditions as will be set on 16CF111; on 16CF111 - defendant would plead to counts #2 and #10 as alleged, remaining counts to be DRI, have complied with victim notification requirements with no response, joint recommendation on count #10 of a withheld sentence and place on probation for of 2 years - concurrent to probation on 16CF37 but consecutive to any jail time that State is asking for on count #2, court costs, #2 - state will argue for 1 year in the FC jail, fine to be determined by the court, defense is free to argue for jail time, DL revocation and IID to be determined by the court, AODA and follow thru, $495.00 to FC Drug Task Force by stipulation on 16CF23, maintain absolute sobriety, take all meds as prescribed and in the manner in which they are prescribed by treating physician, no consumption or possession of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, maintain/obtain full time employment/school and if not full time employed or in school - must compelte 20 hours of community service each week, attend weekly self help at least once per week. Cveykus and Morris agree, Cveykus believes she is eligible for expungment on 16CF37 and not on 16CF111. Court - 16CF23 - dismiss except for $495.00 out of bond posted to be paid to FC Drug Task Force and remainder of bond posted can be put on other cases, 16CF367 - amends count #2 to county ordinance of possession of THC - pleads G, finds G, fine of $1000.00 plus costs - take bond from 16CF23, #3 - amends to county ordinance of possession of drug paraphanalia, pleads G, finds G, fine of $500.00 plus costs - 60 DTP/CO. Morris pleads G to count #1 as alleged on 16CF37. Court - 16CF111 - counts #1, #3, #4, #5, #6, #7, #8, #9 and #11 are to be dismisses and read in. Morris pleads G to counts #2 and #10 on 16CF111. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights by entering her plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - on count #2 - asking for a straight jail sentence of 1 year with no probation and 2 years probation on count #10 with conditions as previoulsy stated. Cveykus makes final argument prior to sentencing - agrees with the probation being consecutive to whatever jail time the Court orders, recommends 60 days in FC jail for stated reasons - provides Court with the defendant's school schedule (State has seen it) - asks for time to report. State makes comment regarding defendant's criminal history. Morris makes statement. Court sentences the defendant to the following: 16CF37 - count #1 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 2 years with conditions of: AODA and follow thru, take all meds as prescribed and in the manner in which they are prescribed by treating physician, no consumption or possession of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, maintain/obtain full time employment/school and if not full time employed or in school (at least 12 credits), attend at least one AA/NA or similar program per week, costs - paid within 60 days/CO; 16CF111 - count #10 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 2 years, concurrent to probation on 16CF37 but consecutive to jail time on count #2, with same conditions as 16CF37 except no additional community service; count #2 - costs - paid within 60 days/CO, impose 1 year in county jail - stayed - serve 90 days and remaining 9 months is stayed as long as a full time student (12 credits or more) or full time employed, if not employed or in school for more than a week and pending compliance with probation conditions on other counts/cases - huber and good time allowed - eligible for community service under 973.03(3) - authorize her release to attend college but will be subject to random UA's and possible body cavity searches- and if these conditions are not complied with - the defendant must service the remaining 9 months in jail - report by 6:00 PM today (12/2/16), submit DNA sample, no possession of firearms, no voting rights, authorizes expungement on 16CF37 under 973.015 as long as all conditions have been complied with, revoke license for 2 years, IID on DL and all vehicles titled in her name for 2 years commencing upon issuance of valid DL, credit for 1 day only if revoked on 16CF37, right to appeal, adjourned.
Jury trial on December 2, 2016 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Keshia Lynne Morris in court with attorney Rick Terrence Cveykus.  Jodie L. Bednar appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 10:17 AM. Called 16CF23, 16CF111 and 16CF37. Cveykus - not resolved - has not received an offer on 16CF23 and 16CF111, has received an offer on 16CF37. Cveykus - recites offer - 16CF111 - plead to counts #1 and #2, dismiss #3 - #6, plead to counts #7, #8 and #9, remainder to be DRI, PSI and free to argue; 16CF23 - dismiss and read in count #1, #2 - plead as alleged - 3 years probation with 120 days jail, dismiss #3, #4 - $100 fine with 3 years probation, #5 and #6 - DRI; 16CF37 - amend all three counts #1 - possession of THC as county ordinance with fine of $1000, #2 - amend to same ordinance with fine of $1000, #3 - amend to county ordinance of possession of para with fine of $500.00. Court goes over Frye with the defendant, defendant understands. Court continues bond on all three matters and will set all three for JT. 16CF111 will be #1, 16CF23 will be #2 and 16CF37 will be #3.  Jury trial scheduled for December 2, 2016 at 08:30 am.
Final pre-trial on August 24, 2016 at 09:30 am.
